hints:
Try to classify solutions to the equation

\begin{align*}\displaystyle x^{2} \equiv 1 \mod{2^{e}}.\end{align*}

This general statement will be useful.

\textbf{Lemma} The solutions to
$\displaystyle x^{2} \equiv 1 \mod{2^{e}}$ for \emph{e} a positive
integer are given as follows:

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
1) If $\displaystyle e=1$, then $\displaystyle x=1$.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
2) If $\displaystyle e=2$, then $\displaystyle x=\pm1$.
\end{description}

\begin{description}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item[]
3) If $\displaystyle e\geq 3$, then
$\displaystyle x\equiv \pm 1 \mod{2^{e}}$ or
$\displaystyle x=\pm1 + 2^{e-1} \mod{2^{e}}$.
\end{description}

With the lemma and the induction hypothesis, what we can do is notice
that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 2^{\alpha-2} \not \equiv 1 \mod{2^{\alpha+1}}\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 2^{\alpha-1} \equiv 1 \mod{2^{\alpha+1}}\end{align*}

gives rise to a nontrivial solution to

\begin{align*}\displaystyle x^{2} \equiv 1 \mod{2^{\alpha+1}}.\end{align*}

We proceed by contradiction assuming (post induction hypothesis) that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 2^{\alpha-1} \equiv 1 \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}\end{align*}

and thus giving

\begin{align*}\displaystyle 2^{\alpha-2} \not \equiv 1 \mod{2^{\alpha+2}}\end{align*}

which is inconsistent with the above.
